  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The most holy house.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The writer proceeds from speaking of \"the greater house\" (ver. 5), or holy place, to the \"holy of holies.\" The parallel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") adds the height, as also 20 cubits",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". Six hundred talents.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It is impossible to assert with any accuracy the money value intended here. Six hundred talents of gold is an amazing proportion of the yearly revenue of 666 talents of gold, spoken of in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This latter amount is worth, in Keil's estimate, about three million and three quarters of our money, but in Peele's estimate nearer double that! The Hebrew, Phoenician, and Assyrian unit of weight is the same, and one quite different from the Egyptian. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "silver",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " talent (Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ciccar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "כִּכָּר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") contained 60 manehs, each maneh being equal to 50 shekels, and a shekel being worth 220 grains; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " there were 3000 shekels, or 660,000 grains, in such talent. But the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gold",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " talent con-rained 100 manehs, the maneh 100 shekels, and the shekel 132 grains, making this gold talent the equivalent of 10,000 shekels, or 1,320,000 grains. The \"holy shekel,\" or \"shekel of the sanctuary,\" could be either of gold or silver (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 38:4, 5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). (For some treatment of this still unsatisfactory subject, see Dr. Smith's . Bible Dictionary,' 3:1727-1736; and Conder's ' Handbook to the Bible,' 2nd edit., pp. 64-78, 81.) 2 Chronicles 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The most holy place, with the figures of the cherubim and the veil; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:19-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - The length of the most holy place in front of the breadth of the house, twenty cubits, consequently measured in the same way as the porch (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); the breadth, i.e., the depth of it, also twenty cubits. The height, which was the same (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is not stated; but instead of that we have the weight of the gold which was used for the gilding, which is omitted in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", viz., 600 talents for the overlaying of the walls, and 50 shekels for the nails to fasten the sheet gold on the wainscotting. He covered the upper chambers of the most holy place also with gold; see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
